==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prest
<hw>Prest</hw> <pr>(pr⟦ecr⟧st)</pr>, <def><pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> of
<er>Press</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prest
<hw>Prest</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>prest</ets>, F.
<ets>pr⟦ecir⟧t</ets>, fr. L. <ets>praestus</ets> ready. Cf.
<er>Presto</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Ready; prompt; prepared.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All <qex>prest</qex> to such battle he was.</q> <rj><qau>R. of
Gloucester.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Neat; tidy; proper.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Tusser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Prest money</b></col>, <cd>money formerly paid to men
when they enlisted into the British service; -- so called because it
bound those that received it to be ready for service when called
upon.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Prest
<hw>Prest</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>prest</ets>, F.
<ets>pr⟦ecir⟧t</ets>, fr. OF. <ets>prester</ets> to lend, F.
<ets>pr⟦ecir⟧ter</ets>, fr. L. <ets>praestare</ets> to stand before, to
become surety for, to fulfill, offer, supply; <ets>prae</ets> before +
<ets>stare</ets> to stand. See <er>Pre-</er>, and <er>Stand</er>, and
cf. <er>Press</er> to force into service.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Ready
money; a loan of money.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Requiring of the city a <qex>prest</qex> of six thousand
marks.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A duty in money formerly paid by
the sheriff on his account in the exchequer, or for money left or
remaining in his hands.</def> <rj><au>Cowell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Prest
<hw>Prest</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To give as a loan; to lend.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sums of money . . . <qex>prested</qex> out in loan.</q>
<rj><qau>E. Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prestable</ent>⟦br⟧
